⚠️ REVIEW PROMPT: This prompt is for reviewing already-generated content. 
- Can be used by ChatGPT O3 Pro for external review
- Can be used by Claude Code when user explicitly requests peer review
- CANNOT be used during initial content generation

**Peer‑Review Checklist – Bibliography (`ref.bib`)**

⚑ **Purpose**  
Ensure that every citation in `ref.bib` is genuine, correctly formatted, and discoverable through standard scholarly indexes (CrossRef, PubMed, Web of Science, arXiv, SSRN, or major conference digital libraries).

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
⟡ *Verification Protocol*  
Follow these steps **for each** `@article`, `@inproceedings`, `@book`, or other entry:

1. **Existence check** (use Playwright MCP for genuine verification when available)  
   • Search the exact *title + first author surname* in Google Scholar and at least one field‑specific index.  
   • Record whether a matching record (same authors, year, venue) appears.  

2. **Metadata fidelity**  
   • Confirm: author list, year, journal / conference name, volume, pages, DOI, arXiv ID, and URL.  
   • Flag discrepancies ≥ 1 field (e.g., wrong year or journal) for correction.  

3. **Accessibility**  
   • Verify that the DOI or persistent URL resolves (HTTP 200).  
   • If pay‑walled, note “paywall” but do **not** flag as fake.  

4. **Relevance**  
   • Skim abstract (or PDF) to ensure the reference is *actually cited* and supports the statement made in the manuscript.  

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
⟡ *Hallucination‑Detection Output* — **Write review opinions in a .md file**  

> **This is a research bibliography. Please search the Internet for every reference to find out potential hallucination references.**  
> **1. List fake references in English (one per line).**  
> **2. For each fake reference, locate a genuine, thematically similar work and provide an in‑text citation suggestion in LaTeX form (e.g., `\citep{Smith2024}`) plus a fully formatted replacement BibTeX entry.**  
> **3. Write review opinions in a .md file**

**Example reporting format (replace with real findings)**  
Fake references detected:
– Doe, J. & Roe, R. (2019) “Deep Unicorn Networks.” Imaginary Journal of AI, 42(3), 1‑10.
– Müller, L. (2020) “Quantum AI for Cats.” Proceedings of the 1st Symposium on Feline Computing, 99‑108.

Proposed replacements:
\citep{Smith2024,Johnson2023}

@article{Smith2024,
author = {Smith, A. and Lee, B.},
title = {Deep Neural Networks for Real‑World Image Classification},
journal = {IEEE Transactions on Pattern Analysis and Machine Intelligence},
year = {2024},
volume = {46},
number = {5},
pages = {1234--1247},
doi = {10.1109/TPAMI.2024.00001}
}

@inproceedings{Johnson2023,
author = {Johnson, C.},
title = {Quantum Machine Learning: A Survey},
booktitle = {Proceedings of NeurIPS 2023},
year = {2023},
pages = {1--15},
url = {https://arxiv.org/abs/2301.01234}
}

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
⟡ *Formatting Audit*  

- **Field completeness:** `author`, `title`, `year`, `journal`/`booktitle`, `volume|number` (if applicable), `pages`, `doi|url`.  
- **LaTeX hygiene:** No unescaped special characters (`& % _ $ # { } ^ ~`).  
- **Consistent casing:** Use sentence‑case or title‑case uniformly per journal guidelines.  
- **Name ordering:** “Surname, Initial.” format for all authors; use `and` between multiple authors.  

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
⟡ *Verdict Flags*  

- ✔ **Accurate** – entry verified, no action.  
- △ **Correctable** – exists but metadata errors; list required fixes.  
- ✗ **Fake/Unverifiable** – list under *Fake references* and supply replacement.  
